06949nam a22009255i 9780231520775DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2011039141  a(OCoLC)979751709  a97802315207757 a10.7312/wein156162doi  a(DE-B1597)459433  a(OCoLC)811404784  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPS88b.A49 2012 4aPS88b.A49 2012 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a810.922200aAmerican Literature’s Aesthetic Dimensions /ced. by Cindy Weinstein, Christopher Looby. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (440 p.) :b‹B›B&W Illus.: ‹/B›.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart 1. Aesthetics and the Politics of Freedom -- t1. Liberty of the Imagination in Revolutionary America -- t2. The Writing on the Wall -- t3. Stephen Crane’s Refrain -- t4. Lyric Citizenship in Post 9/11 Performance -- tPart 2. Aesthetics and the Representation of Sexuality -- t5. Aesthetics Beyond the Actual: The Marble Faun and Romantic Sociality -- t6. Henry James, Constance Fenimore Woolson, and the Figure in the Carpet -- t7. Sexuality’s Aesthetic Dimension -- t8. From Hawthorne to Hairspray -- tPart 3. Aesthetics and the Reading of Form -- t9. When Is Now? -- t10. Reading in the Present Tense -- t11. What Maggie Knew -- t12. Upon a Peak in Beinecke -- tPart 4. Aesthetics and the Question of Theory -- t13. Warped Conjunctions -- t14. Aesthetics and the New Ethics -- t15. Postwar Pastoral -- t16. Perfect Is Dead -- t17. Network Aesthetics -- tAfterword -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRethinking the category of aesthetics in light of recent developments in literary theory and social criticism, the contributors to this volume showcase the interpretive possibilities available to those who bring politics, culture, ideology, and conceptions of identity into their critiques. Essays combine close readings of individual works and authors with more theoretical discussions of aesthetic theory and its relation to American literature. In their introduction, Weinstein and Looby argue that aesthetics never left American literary critique. Instead, the essay casts the current "return to aesthetics" as the natural consequence of shortcomings in deconstruction and new historicism, which led to a reconfiguration of aesthetics. Subsequent essays demonstrate the value and versatility of aesthetic considerations in literature, from eighteenth-century poetry to twentieth-century popular music. Organized into four groups—politics, form, gender, and theory—contributors revisit the canonical works of Henry James, Nathaniel Hawthorne, and Stephen Crane, introduce the overlooked texts of Constance Fenimore Woolson and Earl Lind, and unpack the complexities of the music of The Carpenters. Deeply rooted in an American context, these essays explore literature's aesthetic dimensions in connection to American liberty and the formation of political selfhood.Contributors include Edward Cahill, Ivy G. Wilson, June Ellison, Dorri Beam, Christopher Castiglia, Christopher Looby, Wendy Steiner, Cindy Weinstein, Trish Loughran, Jonathan Freedman, Elisa New, Dorothy Hale, Mary Esteve, Eric Lott, Sianne Ngai  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aLiteraturexAesthetics. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aAltieri, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeam, Dorri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBentley, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aC